@node 000 Afghanistan
Nature and climate: Cold winters and hot summers. Mostly rugged mountains;
   plains in north and southwest.
Natural resources: Natural gas, petroleum, coal, copper, tlac, barites,
   sulphur, lead, zink, iron ore, salt, precious and semiprecious stones.
People: Pasthun 38%, Tajik 25%, Uzbek 6%, Hazara 19% and minor ethnic
   groups.
Independence: 19 August 1919 from UK
History: Conquered in the 4th century BC by Alexander the Great, Afghanistan
   fell under Arab domination in the 7th century AD, before being conquered
   by th Mongols under Genghis Khan. Part of the Indian Mogul empire, it
   became independent in the mid-18th century, and in the 19th and early
   20th century was the focal point for conflicting Russian and British
   interests on the Northwest Frontier, the British fighting three wars
   against the Afghans between 1839 and 1919. A constitutional monarchy
   since 1930, Afghanistan became progressively politically unstable in the
   1970s and was invaded by the Russians in December 1979.
@endnode
@node 001 Albania
Nature and climate: Mostly moutains and hills; small plains along coast.
   Mild temperate climate and wet winters.
Natural resources: Petroleum, natural gas, coal, chromium, copper, timber
   and nickel.
People: Albanian 90%, Greeks 8%, other 2%.
Independence: 28 November 1912 from Ottoman Empire
History: Although Albania was part of the Byzantine empire from the 6th
   century and a part of the Turkish from the 15th century, its mountain
   tribes always remained fiercely independent and central rule was never
   completely effective. It became an independent State as a result of the
   Balkan Wars in 1912, and after a breif period as a republic became a
   rather unstable monarchy under King Zog in 1928. Invaded by Italy in 1939
   it became a Communist State under Enver Hoxha after the Second World War,
   and although first under the influence of the USSR and later under that
   of China, has generally remained isolationist in policy and outlook.
@endnode
@node 006 Argentina
Nature and climate: Rich plains of the Pampas in nothern half, flat to
   rolling plateau of Pantagonia in south and rugged Andes along western
   border.
Natural resources: Fertile plains of the pampas, lead, zinc, tin, copper,
   iron ore, manganese, petroleum and uranium.
People: White 85%, mestizo, Indian, or other nonwhite groups 15%.
Independence: 25 May 1810
History: Colonized by the Spanish in the 16th century, Argentina declared
   its independence in 1810 and played a crucial role in the overthrow of
   European rule in the rest o South America. After a period of semi-
   dictatorial rule, the country emerged as a democratic republic in the
   mid-19th century, but has since had recurrent problems with political
   stability, periodically falling under military rule, most notably at the
   time of Juan Peron. In 1982 th Argentinian claim to the Falkland Islands
   led to an unsuccessful war with Britain.
@endnode
@node 002 Algeria
Nature and climate: Mild, wet winters with hot, dry summers along coast and
   cold winters with hot summers on high plateau. Mostly high plateau and
   desert.
Natural resources: Petroleum, natural gas, iron ore, phosphates, uranium,
   lead and zinc.
People: Arab-Berber 99%, European less than 1%.
Independence: 5 July 1962 from France
History: Algeria came under nominal Turkish rule in the 16th century, but
   the native peoples always retained a high degree of independence,
   dominating the Barbary coast until colonized by France in the mid-19th
   century. Heavily settled by French immigrants, Algeria was closely
   integrated with metropolitan France, but the refusal of the European
   settlers to grant equal rights to the native population led to increasing
   political instability and civil war in the 1950s, and in 1962 the country
   was granted independence as a result of a referendum.
@endnode
