@node 009 Azerbaijan
Nature and climate: Large, flat Kura-Aras Lowland (much of it below sea
   level) with Great Caucasus Mountains to the north and Karabakh Upland in
   west. Dry climate.
Natural resources: Petroleum, natural gas, iron ore, nonferrous metals and
   alumina.
People: Azeri 82.7%, Russian 5.6%, Armenian 5.6%, Daghestanis, 3.2% and
   other 2.9%.
Independence: 30 August 1991 from Soviet Union.
@endnode
@node 010 "Bahamas"
Nature and climate: Long, flat coral formations with some low rounded hills.
   Tropical marine climate, moderated by warm water of Gulf Stream.
Natural resources: Salt, aragonite and timber.
People: Black 85% and white 15%.
Independence: 10 July 1973 from UK
@endnode
@node 011 Bahrain
Nature and climate: Mostly low desert plain rising gently to low central
   escarpment. Mild, pleasant winters and very hot, humid summers.
Natural resources: Oil, associated and nonassociated natural gas, fish
People: Bahraini 63%, Asian 13%, other Arab 10%, Iranian 8% and other 6%.
Independence: 15 August 1971 from UK.
@endnode
@node 012 Bangladesh
Nature and climate: Mostly flat alluvial plain, but hilly in southeast.
   Tropical climate with cool, dry winter (October to March), hot humid
   summer (March to June) and cool rainy monsoon (June to October).
Natural resources: Natural gas, arable land and timber.
People: Bengali 98%, Biharis
Independence: 16 December 1971 from Pakistan.
History: From 1857 the area formed part of India, under British rule, until
   1947 when it became (as East Pakistan) one of the two geographicla units
   of Pakistan. In response to serious internal political problems an
   independent republic was proclaimed in East Pakistan 1971, taking the
   name of Bangladesh, which became a member State of the Commonwealth in
   1972.
@endnode
