@endnode
@node 144 Switzerland
Nature and climate: Mostly mountains (Alps in south and Jura in northwest)
   with a central plateau of rolling hills, plains, and large lakes.
   Temperate climate, byt varies with altitude.
Natural resources: Hydropower potential, timber and salt.
People: German 65%, Italian 10%, Romansch 1%, other 6%.
Independence: 1 August 1291.
History: The area (occupied by a Celtic people, the Helvetii) was under
   Roman rule from the 1st century BC until the the 5th century AD, and from
   the 10th century formed part of the Holy Roman Empire. Switzerland
   emerged as an independent country in the Middle Ages when the local
   cantons joined in league to defeat first their Hapsburg overlords (14th
   century) and then their Burgundian neighbours (15th century). The Swiss
   Confederation maintained neutrality in international affairs through the
   17th and 18th centuries,and after a period of French domination
   (1798-1815), the Confederation's neutrality was guaranteed by the other
   European powers. Neutral in both World Wars, Switzerland has emerged as
   the headquarters of such as the Red Cross.
@endnode
